I just saw this film last night and plan to see it again tonight. I can give my thoughts on it if you need anything, and I won’t spoil.

The best description I can give this film is, that it’s a thrill ride. The adrenaline rush is cranked up all the way from beginning to end. Perhaps as a way to make up for lost time.

You don’t think about things, because it doesn’t give you time to. But if you stop and think about the moments you’re concerned about, you find it touches on a lot of them. Not in the best, or most elaborate of ways, but it does touch upon them. Why Rey does things so easily, what is Snoke, Rey’s parents(who they were and what happened to them), Palpatine’s survival, etc.

If you’re wanting to think about things, this is a film that has a lot of two minute explanations that may not quite satisfy. But if you are looking for a film that is a roller coaster from beginning to end this definitely satisfies and you do get a rush at the end of it.

And the choice of Palpatine? Well, I think it makes sense. To me anyway. It paints him as the main baddie throughout the entire saga, even if he isn’t in all of it. It starts with him, and it ends with him. It also serves as an end to the Skywalker saga in one way, but may begin it in another asking a question of ‘What’s in a name?’

Does this film end the Skywalker saga? Yes it does. Can it continue beyond this? Yes, it can. Should it continue? That’s a question I can’t answer, and won’t try to.

I’ve seen some hater entries so far as ‘the Fandom Menace’ is likely out in full force. I’ve taken them off my recommendations list of videos when they cross my screen. This is not me retreating into a bubble, but me believing they have nothing to offer the conversation. The hate they offer doesn’t provide anything constructive. It is mostly for clickbait purposes, and just encourages people to be....their worst selves. Not their best. So the only thing to say about the Fandom Menace is.....”You have nothing to offer me.”...and you can quote me on that.

I expect you’ll give your grade, but for me I give Rise of Skywalker a B-.

Hope you read this Chris, and I hope this contributes to your Stuckmannization (I know, that’s not a word) of ‘The Rise of Skywalker’. But the trick of enjoying the film here is don’t think too much about it. Sit back, enjoy the ride. Get lost in the rush of the film, because it left me with one.

Absolutely spot on review.

I recently watched all the movies again in preparation for this one and I would say my liking of the prequels HAS improved . The things I thought I didn’t like about the newer movies are actually IN the originals and the prequels. Goofy comedy? How about Chewie making a Tarzan sound while swinging on the vine in Return of the Jedi?

Granted, that kind of thing wasn’t so over the top as it was in the Phantom Menace but still, I don’t remember coming out of Return of the Jedi raging that I’d just seen a full fledged Jedi with no back story, or that it was a rehash of the ole “let’s blow up the Death Star AGAIN”...things that I found myself criticizing in the newer films (vacant back story and/or character development as well as repeated tropes).

What I learned with my rewatching of the films is exactly what you mention - my age and my attitude. They aren’t BAD films...I’m just a different person from that wide eyed kid who walked into the theater in 1977.

I went into this film ignoring my adulthood and I went in just wanting a fictional story that would entertain and take me away for a little bit. I allowed myself to be swallowed by the spectacle and I didn’t think too hard about the details.

And I fuckin had a blast!

Try that if you go see it again. Don’t sit and judge the movie, sit and enjoy it. I’d be curious to see if it helps!

snippet.textDisplay: One of the biggest issues for me that I haven't seen people talk about yet is the editing. Rarely does editing stand out (whether it's good or bad), generally editing is overlooked as long as it's good enough to function with the film. But here, the editing really stood out to myself and friends I saw it with. The pacing of the scenes and the film overall is so awkwardly abrupt - scenes start and end so quickly, never giving audiences time to connect emotionally with what is happening. There's no breathing room, so no tension is built. It feels like video game cut scenes strung together. Within the first 10 minutes of the film, I was already noticing how scenes quickly jumped around - characters would say a couple lines of cheesy "wisdom" type dialogue, then the scene would cut immediately, before anything could sink in emotionally.
